<div id="review_377875172" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/377875172" />
    <a title="Katy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4572741-katy"><img alt="Katy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1365039295p2/4572741.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/377875172?book_show_action=true">Jul 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katy" href="/user/show/4572741-katy">Katy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer377875172" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9783012753432571131">3.5 stars<br/><br/>I found myself liking this more than Slave. Shut up, JP, it&apos;s not because <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[there was actually sex in this book - and hot sex at that <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, but because this book did what a lot of the first book failed to do - connect with the characters.<br/><br/>I liked that this book had pretty much even points of view from Stephan and Brianna because it let me how differently two people perceive the same scene. Also, in book 1, I was unable to really feel Stephan&apos;s frustration and Bria</span>
  <span id="freeText9783012753432571131" style="display:none">3.5 stars<br /><br />I found myself liking this more than Slave. Shut up, JP, it's not because <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[there was actually sex in this book - and hot sex at that <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, but because this book did what a lot of the first book failed to do - connect with the characters.<br /><br />I liked that this book had pretty much even points of view from Stephan and Brianna because it let me how differently two people perceive the same scene. Also, in book 1, I was unable to really feel Stephan's frustration and Brianna's confusion, and I was able to tap into those feelings more in this book.<br /><br />I also felt the storyline outside of their relationship was more developed in this book. I liked how Logan and Lily - and even Uncle Richard - were more involved in their lives. And I got to know more behind Anna's story, and we begin to see a little more about the sheriff-and-Ian question that really bugged me in book 1.<br /><br />But, honestly, I'm not sure BDSM is my cup of tea. I didn't like <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the use of the leash at the mall. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> I guess what people do behind closed doors is their own business, but when it's displayed out in public like that, it makes me a little uncomfortable. It's not that I have a big problem with it, but like I said, it's not really my thing.<br /><br />Overall, not a bad read, and I'll probably read the next book because I'm curious about the cliffhanger. And this time, there was a "real cliffhanger," not an abrupt stop like the first book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9783012753432571131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

